
[1]parch

   P`ARCH, v.t. [I know not from what source we have received this word.
   It corresponds in elements with the Italian bruciare, to burn or roast.
   Qu. L. peraresco.]

   1. To burn the surface of a thing; to scorch; as, to parch the skin; to
   parch corn.

   2. To dry to extremity; as, the heat of the sun's rays parches the
   ground; the mouth is parched with thirst.

    P`ARCH, v.i. To be scorched or superficially burnt; as, corn will dry
                           and parch into barley.

   1. To become very dry.
